(General) Linear Models Report

Source: R/report.glm.R
report.lm.Rd

Create a report of a (general) linear model.

# S3 method for lm
report(model, ci = 0.95, standardize = TRUE,
  effsize = "cohen1988", performance_in_table = TRUE,
  performance_metrics = "all", bootstrap = FALSE, iterations = 500,
  ...)

# S3 method for glm
report(model, ci = 0.95, standardize = TRUE,
  effsize = "chen2010", performance_in_table = TRUE,
  performance_metrics = "all", bootstrap = FALSE, iterations = 500,
  ...)

Arguments

model

Object of class lm.
ci

Confidence Interval (CI) level. Default to 0.95 (95%).
standardize

Standardized coefficients. See model_parameters.
effsize

Interpret the standardized parameters using a set of rules. Can be "cohen1988" (default for linear models), "chen2010" (default for logistic models), "sawilowsky2009", NULL, or a custom set of rules.
performance_in_table

Add performance metrics in table.
performance_metrics

See model_performance.
bootstrap

See model_parameters.
iterations

The number of bootstrap replicates. This only apply in the case of bootsrapped frequentist models.
...

Arguments passed to or from other methods.

Examples

model <- lm(Sepal.Length ~ Petal.Length * Species, data = iris)
r <- report(model)
to_text(r)
#> We fitted a linear model to predict Sepal.Length with Petal.Length and Species. The model's explanatory power is substantial (R2 = 0.84, adj. R2 = 0.83). The model's intercept is at 4.21. 
#> 
#> Within this model: 
#>   - Petal.Length is not significant (beta = 0.54, 95% CI [-0.00, 1.09], p = 0.05) and large (std. beta = 1.16).
#>   - Speciesversicolor is significant (beta = -1.81, 95% CI [-2.99, -0.62], p < .01) and large (std. beta = -0.88).
#>   - Speciesvirginica is significant (beta = -3.15, 95% CI [-4.41, -1.90], p < .001) and large (std. beta = -1.75).
#>   - Petal.Length:Speciesversicolor is not significant (beta = 0.29, 95% CI [-0.30, 0.87], p > .1) and medium (std. beta = 0.61).
#>   - Petal.Length:Speciesvirginica is not significant (beta = 0.45, 95% CI [-0.12, 1.03], p > .1) and large (std. beta = 0.97).
to_fulltext(r)
#> We fitted a linear model (using OLS algorithm) to predict Sepal.Length with Petal.Length and Species (formula = Sepal.Length ~ Petal.Length * Species). Effect sizes were labelled following Cohen's (1988) recommendations. The model explains a not significant and substantial proportion of variance (R2 = 0.84, F(, ) = , p , adj. R2 = 0.83). The model's intercept, corresponding to Petal.Length = 0 and Species = , is at 4.21 (t(144) = 10.34, 95% CI [3.41, 5.02], p < .001).

#>   - Speciesversicolor is negative, significant (beta = -1.81, SE = 0.60, t(144) = -3.02, 95% CI [-2.99, -0.62], p < .01) and large (std. beta = -0.88, std. SE = 0.77, std. 95% CI [-2.41, 0.65]).
#>   - Speciesvirginica is negative, significant (beta = -3.15, SE = 0.63, t(144) = -4.97, 95% CI [-4.41, -1.90], p < .001) and large (std. beta = -1.75, std. SE = 0.79, std. 95% CI [-3.32, -0.18]).
#>   - Petal.Length:Speciesversicolor is positive, not significant (beta = 0.29, SE = 0.30, t(144) = 0.97, 95% CI [-0.30, 0.87], p > .1) and medium (std. beta = 0.61, std. SE = 0.63, std. 95% CI [-0.63, 1.85]).
#>   - Petal.Length:Speciesvirginica is positive, not significant (beta = 0.45, SE = 0.29, t(144) = 1.56, 95% CI [-0.12, 1.03], p > .1) and large (std. beta = 0.97, std. SE = 0.62, std. 95% CI [-0.26, 2.19]).

model <- glm(vs ~ disp, data = mtcars, family = "binomial")
r <- report(model)
to_text(r)
#> We fitted a logistic model to predict vs with disp. The model's explanatory power is substantial (Tjur's R2 = 0.53). The model's intercept is at 4.14. 
#> 
#> Within this model: 
#>   - disp is significant (beta = -0.02, 95% CI [-0.04, -0.01], p < .01) and large (std. beta = -2.68).
to_fulltext(r)
#> We fitted a logistic model (using ML algorithm) to predict vs with disp (formula = vs ~ disp). Effect sizes were labelled following Chen's (2010) recommendations. The model's explanatory power is substantial (Tjur's R2 = 0.53). The model's intercept, corresponding to disp = 0, is at 4.14 (z = 2.98, 95% CI [1.81, 7.44], p < .01). 
#> 
#> Within this model: 
#>   - disp is negative, significant (beta = -0.02, SE = 0.01, z = -3.03, 95% CI [-0.04, -0.01], p < .01) and large (std. beta = -2.68, std. SE = 0.88, std. 95% CI [-4.90, -1.27]).
